        <h1>WHY MOST CREATORS STAY BROKE</h1>
        <p>Most creators post every day, reply to every DM, spend hours on content — and still barely break $500/month.</p>
        <p>The problem isn't effort. It's the absence of a system.</p>
        <p>Without a structure that turns attention into income, you're just creating for free. Agencies know this. That's why they take 50–70% — they bolt on the system you're missing.</p>
        <p>This guide eliminates that dependency. You keep 100%.</p>
        <p>What actually separates top earners from everyone else has very little to do with luck. It is not purely about appearance, nor is it defined by content quality alone. The difference is far more deliberate. It is strategy.</p>
        <p>Over time, certain patterns become impossible to ignore. Creators who approach this as a business begin to see consistent progress. They refine, adjust, and build systems around what they do, while those who rely on hope — posting without direction, waiting for momentum to appear — often burn out or quietly disappear.</p>
        <p>This understanding did not come easily. I went through most of the challenges alone, and it came at a cost. Time, money, energy, and lost momentum. I had to rebuild more than once, rebrand when I had already come too far to justify starting over, yet too little structure to move forward.</p>
        <p>I spent time studying. Learning marketing. Testing what works, what doesn't, and why. I invested hours into understanding attention, conversion, psychology, and positioning. I made mistakes, lost money, wasted time — and then did it again, but smarter.</p>
        <p>There were no shortcuts, no sudden breakthroughs — just patterns that slowly started to make sense. What once felt random became predictable. What once felt frustrating became controllable. And that is where everything changed.</p>
        <p>This guide exists for a single reason: to help you avoid my mistakes.</p>
